segments.text: It seems that this short war, which took place just a few months earlier, changed the entire country.
And when Rolf entered her life, the country was the heroine that knew how to defeat its surrounding enemies in just six days.
Something of this atmosphere and the exalted patriotic feeling also clung to her, knowing that soon she was about to be part of this important and victorious army.
Carmela Zevik, who was one of the first paratroopers and was once a parachuting instructor in the Army, had a conversation with her one day and urged her to aim for leadership.
You have all the skills for it, he said.
She promised him.
She didn't quite understand what exactly awaited her, but somehow she wasn't really scared of it.
what will come will come, and Rolf, like Zevik, also had the serious talk with her.
About a month before her enlistment, he suddenly told her, with a serious expression on his face, you know they'll quickly make you an officer.
She laughed in surprise.
Why would they?
It's not certain at all.
What special skills do I have?
It's not sure if I'm suitable at all.
In the end, they'll probably make me a clerk and that's not so bad.
No, he said, and not even a hint of a smile crossed his face.
They will immediately see who they're dealing with.
If they offer it to you, agree, it will be good for your life later.
You'll be able to make a living from it and have a good income.
What do you mean who they're dealing with?
She asked, pretending to be offended.
You mean the fact that I play the piano, am crazy about Frank Sinatra, collect poetry books, recite Edgar Allan Poe in English, and know how to pour beer without foam?
Will convince them that I'm especially talented for officership?
Don't be cynical, he requested in a quiet and slightly reproachful voice.
You are mature.
Responsible and conduct yourself calmly, not frightened by difficulties, not frightened by life, and these are qualities they surely need.
Then he added with a half smile, while stroking her head.
You forgot to mention the great sandwiches with roast beef and mustard you know how to make.
She knew he was worried about what would happen to her after he left.
It seemed that only she wasn't worried.
She developed a magnificent denial mechanism, convincing herself that everything would be okay.
If she had to describe herself at that time, she would say she probably forced herself into a winter hibernation.
Trying to freeze time, to freeze situations, hoping nothing would move and everything would remain in place as it is.

More and more she found herself curling into herself, spiraling, shrinking deep into the armchair in the corner, watching the evening fall, the light dimming and not bothering to turn on the lights, fading into the time she was stopping in its tracks.
This was her way of mourning this house that soon would be no more.
Not for her.

This pink hotel, which for her is first and foremost a house, a whole world in its beauty, its contents, with the large and blossoming garden around it, with Joseph's paintings on the walls, and the piano in the corner.
This is her home.
She doesn't have another and never did.
No matter where she will live later, they will never be this home.
They will not have her corners where she hides and finds peace, and most importantly, they will not have the people who shared life there with her.
Nor the love found between its walls, which instills in her the security that there is always a place to come to.
The place that always has an open door for you, which is just yours, and always welcomes you with open arms.
Others might cry, be angry at the cruel fate at what happened.

But she was still quiet, hoping, not quite believing it was possible, thinking that maybe as she curls and curls into the armchair, if she turns back time, if she holds her breath, maybe everything will change and turn out to be a bad dream.
How do you transition from a joyful childhood, full of experiences and carefree in the wonderland of her pink house to adulthood filled with deprivation, helplessness?
and terrible frustration for the past two years since Lucy.
Passed away, she hadn't cried.
And just when she thought that tears might come, they stopped on their own a second earlier.
As if refusing to flow, knowing that outwardly, she collected herself and projected strength and in no way wanted to appear pitiable.
Nobody knows, and no one will ever know.
In the end, it was the stormy weather that broke her spirit.
Torrential rain poured down for hours as if wanting to unleash all its waters at once without ceasing for a minute.
It wasn't a cleansing rain that washes and cleans and leaves behind a refreshing scent.
It was an angry furious rain, pounding, striking wildly at everything in its path, deafening with no place to escape.
It was late at night, and she was completely alone.
The wind howled outside, and through the large glass doors facing the garden, one could see the sign under the street lamp swaying back and forth with the wind.
the pink house, boarding house, bar, restaurant.
This storm intensified her feelings of loneliness and helplessness.
There wasn't a soul around, and it wasn't a house that knew how to be alone.
It was a house that needed people in it, people to pamper, feed, and host, so they would feel good in it, as if it were their own home.
But those days were gone, and only a few people still visited this inn.
That night, with the silence that reigned and the never-ending rain, the wind's howls sounded like a farewell song to the pink inn.
To this inn that lived full and rich lives, through which thousands passed during its lifetime, fill in its days with countless events and experiences, even evenings of dancing.
How did it fall from grace?
How did this house drain of its life force, from the qualities woven into it by Lucy and Yosef, from the culture and joy that gathered all the nation's greats and bohemians to it?
They poured all of their personality into it, and it was a template of their essence.
But with Lucy's passing and due to her half-sisters' inexplicable greed, the house gradually fell apart from everything it was.

all her attempts to hold onto it, to water the Great Garden so it wouldn't wither, so Lucy wouldn't be saddened if she happened to glance from above, to try to preserve even a little of its magical atmosphere, failed.
Soon, in two months, its doors would close, and it was unknown what fate awaited it, and even more so what fate awaited her.
Now she was nestled deep in Lucy and Yosef's soft armchair, her feet tucked beneath her.
Only a faint light burned above her.
She was aware of the very late hour, but couldn't bring herself to rise from the armchair.

And so, curled up, staring into the darkness outside, and at the sign swaying under the street lamp, letting the fear of what was to come and the melancholy seep into her, she sought to use every additional hour she could still spend in her pink inn.
She knew no other home.
Since she could remember, she had shared her life lovingly with unknown guests, experienced in it all the joys as well as the sad days, the holidays and merely the ordinary days.
She didn't know how to live in other houses, normal houses.
Maybe it was good that she was about to spend the next year and a half in the army, in a framework where they tell her what to do, when, and how, and there is also enough food.
But where will she go on leaves?
Where will she live?
How did she let the storm around her take over?
Where did the courage of the last two years disappear to?
And what happened to that bucket full of pink paint and the brush with which she painted her life in the hope that indeed it would be good?
And now these moments wreak havoc on her soul, turning the picture's colors to the black and gray of reality.
And she must take a deep breath and let them pass.

While she remained curled in the armchair late at night, in the surrounding darkness, with the pouring rain, the winds howls outside, and the signs swaying under the streetlamp, the words of the song seem to rise from somewhere, as if written especially for her.
A person dwells within themselves, whether in some stormy city or some village, sometimes a. Storm passes, sometimes their home breaks, but mostly a person dwells within themselves.
and she knew that whatever happens, that would always be her home deep inside herself.
